TY  - JOUR
T1  - Two Strategies for Inductive Reasoning in Organizational Research
AU  - Ketokivi, Mikko
AU  - Mantere, Saku
Y1  - 2010/04/01
PY  - 2010
DA  - 2010/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.35.2.zok315
DO  - 10.5465/amr.35.2.zok315
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 315
EP  - 333
VL  - 35
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Incompleteness of inductive reasoning presents an enduring dilemma for organizational researchers. We examine two practical reasoning strategies?idealization and contextualization?that can be used at the pinnacle of this dilemma: when theoretical conclusions are drawn from empirical data. Understanding the two strategies can lead to more effective argumentation and evaluation. Appreciating the methodological incompleteness of both strategies, in turn, helps us distinguish between the methodological and the policy dimensions of organization-scientific debates.
AB  - Incompleteness of inductive reasoning presents an enduring dilemma for organizational researchers. We examine two practical reasoning strategies?idealization and contextualization?that can be used at the pinnacle of this dilemma: when theoretical conclusions are drawn from empirical data. Understanding the two strategies can lead to more effective argumentation and evaluation. Appreciating the methodological incompleteness of both strategies, in turn, helps us distinguish between the methodological and the policy dimensions of organization-scientific debates.
